{"title_page": "William Johnson (English politician)", "text_new": "'''William Johnson''' (c. 1660 - 1718)  of Blackwall, Middlesex, and Mandeville's Manor, [[Sternfield]], Aldeburgh, Suffolk, was an English merchant, shipbuilder and Tory politician who sat in the [[English House of Commons|English]] and [[House of Commons of Great Britain|British House of Commons]] for 29 years from 1689 to 1718\n\n==Early life==\nJohnson was the second son of [[Henry Johnson (1623-1683)|Sir Henry Johnson]]  and his wife Dorothy Lord, daughter of William Lord of Melton, Kent. He was educated at Leyden in 1678. He went  to Bengal as a factor for the [[East India Company]] and sometime after 1683, he returned to England and established himself as a merchant, trading to Africa and the Peninsula.<ref name=HOP/> He bought  Mandeville's Manor, Sternfield, near Aldeburgh,<ref>[https://archive.org/details/cu31924092579584/page/n179 The Manors of Suffolk Sternfield]</ref>  but lived mainly  near the shipyard inherited by his brother [[Henry Johnson (died 1719)|Henry]] at [[Blackwall Yard|Blackwall]]. By 1687, he married Agneta Baron, daughter of Hartgill Baron, clerk of the privy seal, of Windsor, Berkshire.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1660-1690/member/johnson-william-1660-1718| title= JOHNSON, William (c.1660-1718), of Blackwall, Mdx.| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1660-1690)| accessdate = 6 July 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFrom 1687 to 1689 Johnson was an Assistant of the [[Royal African Company]].  At the [[1689 English general election]], he was returned as Tory  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Aldeburgh (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldeburgh]] on the  interest of his brother Henry. Also in 1689, he was appointed Commissioner for assessment, for Middlesex, Suffolk and Aldeburgh to 1690, and Deputy Lieutenant for Tower Hamlets at least to 1702.  He was not active in the Convention Parliament, but served on six committees including one to consider the management of the East India trade, one for the bill for restoring corporations, and one on a petition from the Royal Africa Company.<ref name=HOP/>     \n\nJohnson was returned for Aldeburgh in a contest at the [[1690 English general election]]. On 2 April 1690 he was appointed to draft a bill to regulate the East India trade. He was appointed a [[Gentleman of the privy chamber]] from  1690 to 1702. He was also a committee member of the East India Company from 1690 to 1691. With his brother, Sir Henry, he was part of a syndicate that from 1691 to 1694 tried unsuccessfully to challenge  the East India Company's monopoly. He was returned unopposed for Aldeburgh at the [[1695 English general election]] and was appointed on 20 February  to prepare a bill to regulate the East India Company. He signed the Association in February, and in March voted against fixing the price of [[Guinea (coin)|guineas]] at 22 shillings. On 25 November 1696, he voted against the attainder of [[Sir John Fenwick, 3rd Baronet|Sir John Fenwick]].  With  his brother, he returned to the East India Company, and was committee member from 1698 to 1699.<ref name = HOP2>{{cite web| url =  http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1690-1715/member/johnson-william-1660-1718| title=JOHNSON, William (c.1660-1718), of Blackwall, Mdx. and Mandeville\u2019s Manor, Sternfield, Aldeburgh, Suff. | publisher= History of Parliament Online (1690-1715)| accessdate = 7 July  2019 }}</ref>  \n\nAt the [[1698 English general election]], Johnson and his brother both stood at Aldeburgh, where they were returned unopposed again, and he stood on his own at [[Orford (UK Parliament constituency)|Orford]], where he was defeated. He petitioned, and then in February 1700, he went on a long voyage to the East Indies and China. The petition was finally declared in his favour after the dissolution of Parliament. From  the  first general election of 1701, he stood only at Aldeburgh, where he was returned unopposed  then and in the second general election of that year. As a Tory, he  supported the motion of 26 February 1702 to vindicate the Commons\u2019 proceedings over the impeachment of the Whig  ministers in the previous session. He was committee member of the East India Company again  from 1702 to 1705. He was   is not recorded as voting  on the Tack  on 28 November 1704.<ref name=HOP2/>\n[[File:Poplar & Blackwall 1703.jpg|thumb|right|Poplar and Blackwall dock, 1703]]\nJohnson's brother Henry having inherited their father's ship building yard at Blackwall, ran it using a succession  of managers. By 1704 William Johnson was running of the business, and between 1704 and 1710  built five ships-of-the-line and six other vessels there. He was living in the house in the yard from at least 1705, and probably lived there over a longer period.<ref name=BHO>{{cite web |url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/survey-london/vols43-4/pp553-565  |title= 'Blackwall Yard: Development, to c.1819', in Survey of London: Volumes 43 and 44, Poplar, Blackwall and Isle of Dogs, |  pages =553-565| author=  Hermione Hobhouse (ed.) |publisher= British History Online|    accessdate =  7 July 2019 }}</ref> In 1709 he became an Elder Brother of  [[Trinity House]] for the rest of his life.<ref name=HOP2/>  \n\nJohnson was returned unopposed at the [[1705 English general election]] and was absent from the vote on the Speaker on 25 October 1705. He was returned as usual as a Tory at the  [[1708 British general election]] and voted against the impeachment of Dr Sacheverell in 1710.  After the [[1710 British general election]] he  was listed  among the \u2018Tory patriots\u2019 who opposed the continuation of the war, and the \u2018worthy patriots\u2019 who exposed the mismanagements of the previous ministry. He was appointed Commissioner for sewers for [[Tower Hamlets]] in  1712. <ref name=HOP2/> \n\nAt the [[1715 British general election]] Johnson was returned for Aldeburgh for the last time. He voted against the septennial bill. In 1716, he took the post of governor of [[Guinea (region)|Guinea]] ([[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]])  under the Royal African Company, and sailed soon after 16 December 1716<ref name = HOP3>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/johnson-william-1661-1718 | title=JOHNSON, William (aft.1661-1718), of Blackwall, Mdx. | publisher= History of Parliament Online (1715-1754)| accessdate = 7 July  2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nJohnson  was reported to have died at [[Cape Coast Castle]] in November 1718. He and his wife had three sons and nine daughters.  All his property was to be sold, and the proceeds divided equally among the surviving members of his family, except for his one married daughter.<ref name=HOP2/> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n \n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|en}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[John Bence]]\n | before2 = [[Henry Bedingfield (judge)|Sir Henry Bedingfield]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n| title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Aldeburgh (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldeburgh]]\n | years =   [[1689 English general election|1689]]\u20131707  \n | with  =  [[Henry Johnson (died 1719)|Sir Henry Johnson]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = Parliament of Great Britain\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Charles Hedges|Sir Charles Hedges]]\n | before2 = [[Sir Thomas Felton, 4th Baronet|Sir Thomas Felton]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Orford (UK Parliament constituency)|Orford]]\n | years =     1700\u20131701  \n | with  =  [[Sir Edmund Bacon, 4th Baronet, of Mildenhall|Sir Edmund Bacon]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Sir Edmund Bacon, 4th Baronet, of Mildenhall|Sir Edmund Bacon]]\n | after2 = [[Edward Turnour (died 1751)|Sir Edward Turnor]]\n}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = Parliament of England\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Aldeburgh (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldeburgh]]\n | years =     1707\u20131718  \n | with  =  [[Henry Johnson (died 1719)|Sir Henry Johnson]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Henry Johnson (died 1719)|Sir Henry Johnson]]\n | after2 = [[Samuel Lowe]]\n}}\n \n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, William}}\n[[Category:1660s births]]\n[[Category:1718 deaths]]\n [[Category:People from Aldeburgh]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1689\u20131690]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1690\u20131695]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1695\u20131698]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1698\u20131700]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1701]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1701\u20131702]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1702\u20131705]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1705\u20131707]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1707\u20131708]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1708\u20131710]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1710\u20131713]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1713\u20131715]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1715\u20131722]]\n [[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople in shipping]]\n[[Category:British shipbuilders]]\n", "text_old": "'''William Johnson''' (c. 1660 - 1718)  of Blackwall, Middlesex, and Mandeville\u2019s Manor, [[Sternfield]], Aldeburgh, Suffolk, was an English merchant, shipbuilder and Tory politician who sat in the [[English House of Commons|English]] and [[House of Commons of Great Britain|British House of Commons]] for 29 years from 1689 to 1718\n\n==Early life==\nJohnson was the second son of [[Henry Johnson (1623-1683)|Sir Henry Johnson]]  and his wife Dorothy Lord, daughter of William Lord of Melton, Kent. He was educated at Leyden in 1678. He went  to Bengal as a factor for the [[East India Company]] and sometime after 1683, he returned to England and established himself as a merchant, trading to Africa and the Peninsula.<ref name=HOP/> He bought  Mandeville\u2019s Manor, Sternfield, near Aldeburgh,<ref>[https://archive.org/details/cu31924092579584/page/n179 The Manors of Suffolk Sternfield]</ref>  but lived mainly  near the shipyard inherited by his brother [[Henry Johnson (died 1719)|Henry]] at [[Blackwall Yard|Blackwall]]. By 1687, he married Agneta Baron, daughter of Hartgill Baron, clerk of the privy seal, of Windsor, Berkshire.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1660-1690/member/johnson-william-1660-1718| title= JOHNSON, William (c.1660-1718), of Blackwall, Mdx.| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1660-1690)| accessdate = 6 July 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFrom 1687 to 1689 Johnson was an Assistant of the [[Royal African Company]].  At the [[1689 English general election]], he was returned as Tory  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Aldeburgh (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldeburgh]] on the  interest of his brother Henry. Also in 1689, he was appointed Commissioner for assessment, for Middlesex, Suffolk and Aldeburgh to 1690, and Deputy Lieutenant for Tower Hamlets at least to 1702.  He was not active in the Convention Parliament, but served on six committees including one to consider the management of the East India trade, one for the bill for restoring corporations, and one on a petition from the Royal Africa Company.<ref name=HOP/>     \n\nJohnson was returned for Aldeburgh in a contest at the [[1690 English general election]]. On 2 April 1690 he was appointed to draft a bill to regulate the East India trade. He was appointed a [[Gentleman of the privy chamber]] from  1690 to 1702. He was also a committee member of the East India Company from 1690 to 1691. With his brother, Sir Henry, he was part of a syndicate that from 1691 to 1694 tried unsuccessfully to challenge  the East India Company\u2019s monopoly. He was returned unopposed for Aldeburgh at the [[1695 English general election]] and was appointed on 20 February  to prepare a bill to regulate the East India Company. He signed the Association in February, and in March voted against fixing the price of [[Guinea (coin)|guineas]] at 22 shillings. On 25 November 1696, he voted against the attainder of [[Sir John Fenwick, 3rd Baronet|Sir John Fenwick]].  With  his brother, he returned to the East India Company, and was committee member from 1698 to 1699.<ref name = HOP2>{{cite web| url =  http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1690-1715/member/johnson-william-1660-1718| title=JOHNSON, William (c.1660-1718), of Blackwall, Mdx. and Mandeville\u2019s Manor, Sternfield, Aldeburgh, Suff. | publisher= History of Parliament Online (1690-1715)| accessdate = 7 July  2019 }}</ref>  \n\nAt the [[1698 English general election]], Johnson and his brother both stood at Aldeburgh, where they were returned unopposed again, and he stood on his own at [[Orford (UK Parliament constituency)|Orford]], where he was defeated. He petitioned, and then in February 1700, he went on a long voyage to the East Indies and China. The petition was finally declared in his favour after the dissolution of Parliament. From  the  first general election of 1701, he stood only at Aldeburgh, where he was returned unopposed  then and in the second general election of that year. As a Tory, he  supported the motion of 26 February 1702 to vindicate the Commons\u2019 proceedings over the impeachment of the Whig  ministers in the previous session. He was committee member of the East India Company again  from 1702 to 1705. He was   is not recorded as voting  on the Tack  on 28 November 1704.<ref name=HOP2/>\n[[File:Poplar & Blackwall 1703.jpg|thumb|right|Poplar and Blackwall dock, 1703]]\nJohnson\u2019s brother Henry having inherited their father\u2019s ship building yard at Blackwall, ran it using a succession  of managers. By 1704 William Johnson was running of the business, and between 1704 and 1710  built five ships-of-the-line and six other vessels there. He was living in the house in the yard from at least 1705, and probably lived there over a longer period.<ref name=BHO>{{cite web |url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/survey-london/vols43-4/pp553-565  |title= 'Blackwall Yard: Development, to c.1819', in Survey of London: Volumes 43 and 44, Poplar, Blackwall and Isle of Dogs, |  pages =553-565| author=  Hermione Hobhouse (ed.) |publisher= British History Online|    accessdate =  7 July 2019 }}</ref> In 1709 he became an Elder Brother of  [[Trinity House]] for the rest of his life.<ref name=HOP2/>  \n\nJohnson was returned unopposed at the [[1705 English general election]] and was absent from the vote on the Speaker on 25 October 1705. He was returned as usual as a Tory at the  [[1708 British general election]] and voted against the impeachment of Dr Sacheverell in 1710.  After the [[1710 British general election]] he  was listed  among the \u2018Tory patriots\u2019 who opposed the continuation of the war, and the \u2018worthy patriots\u2019 who exposed the mismanagements of the previous ministry. He was appointed Commissioner for sewers for [[Tower Hamlets]] in  1712. <ref name=HOP2/> \n\nAt the [[1715 British general election]] Johnson was returned for Aldeburgh for the last time. He voted against the septennial bill. In 1716, he took the post of governor of [[Guinea (region)|Guinea]] ([[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]])  under the Royal African Company, and sailed soon after 16 December 1716<ref name = HOP3>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/johnson-william-1661-1718 | title=JOHNSON, William (aft.1661-1718), of Blackwall, Mdx. | publisher= History of Parliament Online (1715-1754)| accessdate = 7 July  2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nJohnson  was reported to have died at [[Cape Coast Castle]] in November 1718. He and his wife had three sons and nine daughters.  All his property was to be sold, and the proceeds divided equally among the surviving members of his family, except for his one married daughter.<ref name=HOP2/> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n \n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|en}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[John Bence]]\n | before2 = [[Henry Bedingfield (judge)|Sir Henry Bedingfield]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n| title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Aldeburgh (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldeburgh]]\n | years =   [[1689 English general election|1689]]\u20131707  \n | with  =  [[Henry Johnson (died 1719)|Sir Henry Johnson]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = Parliament of Great Britain\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Charles Hedges|Sir Charles Hedges]]\n | before2 = [[Sir Thomas Felton, 4th Baronet|Sir Thomas Felton]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Orford (UK Parliament constituency)|Orford]]\n | years =     1700\u20131701  \n | with  =  [[Sir Edmund Bacon, 4th Baronet, of Mildenhall|Sir Edmund Bacon]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Sir Edmund Bacon, 4th Baronet, of Mildenhall|Sir Edmund Bacon]]\n | after2 = [[Edward Turnour (died 1751)|Sir Edward Turnor]]\n}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = Parliament of England\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Aldeburgh (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldeburgh]]\n | years =     1707\u20131718  \n | with  =  [[Henry Johnson (died 1719)|Sir Henry Johnson]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Henry Johnson (died 1719)|Sir Henry Johnson]]\n | after2 = [[Samuel Lowe]]\n}}\n \n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, William}}\n[[Category:1660s births]]\n[[Category:1718 deaths]]\n [[Category:People from Aldeburgh]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1689\u20131690]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1690\u20131695]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1695\u20131698]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1698\u20131700]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1701]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1701\u20131702]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1702\u20131705]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1705\u20131707]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1707\u20131708]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1708\u20131710]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1710\u20131713]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1713\u20131715]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1715\u20131722]]\n [[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople in shipping]]\n[[Category:British shipbuilders]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (5)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Johnson_(English_politician)"}
{"title_page": "Chris Oliver (surgeon)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   = Professor\n| name               = Christopher William Oliver\n| honorific_suffix   =\n| image              = Professor-Chris-Oliver.jpg\n| birth_date         =\n| birth_place        = Forest Gate, London, England\n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| occupation         = Surgeon\n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| alma_mater         = [[University College Hospital]], [[University College London]]\n| workplaces         = [[University of Edinburgh]], [[Napier University]]\n| website            = https://cyclingsurgeon.bike/\n}}\n\n'''Chris Oliver''' Edinburgh orthopaedic surgeon/professor. King James IV Professor Royal College of Surgeons of Edinburgh 2019-20<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rcsed.ac.uk/professional-support-development-resources/grants-jobs-and-placements/research-travel-and-award-opportunities/awards-and-medals|title=Awards and Medals {{!}} The Royal College of Surgeons of Edinburgh|work=The Royal College of Surgeons of Edinburgh|access-date=2018-09-29|language=en}}</ref>. Associate Research Fellow, School of Engineering and Built Environment, [[Transport Research Institute]], Edinburgh Napier University 2018-<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.napier.ac.uk/tri/2019/02/04/chris-oliver-appointed-associate-research-fellow-at-tri/|title=Chris Oliver - appointed Associate Research Fellow at TRI|last=yvonnelawrie|date=2019-02-04|website=Transport Research Institute|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref>. Honorary [[Professor]] in Physical Activity for Health at the [[Moray House School of Education|Physical Activity for Health Research Centre]], [[University of Edinburgh]] 2015-2018.<ref name=\"PAHRC ed.ac.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.research.ed.ac.uk/portal/en/persons/chris-oliver(4d8f0274-4cb1-4333-9ef1-e8e282d053b2).html|title=Chris Oliver, University of Edinburgh Research Explorer|last=|first=|date=|website=Univeristy of Edinburgh|publisher=University of Edinburgh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref> Consultant Trauma [[Orthopedic surgery|Orthopaedic]] and Hand Surgeon at [[Royal Infirmary of Edinburgh]] 1997-2017.\n\n==Education==\nIn 1992, Oliver completed a doctorate ([[Doctor of Medicine|MD]]) from [[University College London]] in spinal muscle physiology and artificial intelligence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.research.ed.ac.uk/portal/en/publications/development-of-surface-electromyographic-spectral-analysis-techniques-for-assessing-paraspinal-muscle-function(74669c81-eb8d-4aa8-abff-f78e3e20844e).html|title= Edinburgh Research Explorer: Development of surface electromyographic spectral analysis techniques for assessing paraspinal muscle function |publisher=www.research.ed.ac.uk|accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nOliver retired in 2018 from the [[Royal Infirmary of Edinburgh]] as a Consultant Trauma Orthopaedic Surgeon in the Department of Trauma and Orthopaedics, [[University of Edinburgh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ed.ac.uk/clinical-sciences/orthopaedics-trauma/staff/consultants|title=Department of Orthopaedics and Trauma - The University of Edinburgh|website=ed.ac.uk  |date=18 July 2016|accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref> Career was profiled by the British Medical Journal, Careers  in July 2018<ref>{{Cite journal|last=O\u2019Dowd|first=Adrian|date=2018-05-31|title=Chris Oliver: from orthopaedic surgeon to fitness professor|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/361/bmj.k1768|journal=BMJ|language=en|volume=361|pages=k1768|doi=10.1136/bmj.k1768|issn=0959-8138|pmid=29853632|doi-access=free}}</ref>.\n\nBetween 2015-2018 he was honorary Professor of Physical Activity for Health to [[Moray House School of Education|Physical Activity for Health Research Centre (PAHRC)]] at the [[University of Edinburgh]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.ed.ac.uk/news/staff/appointments-awards/2015/chris-oliver-120615|title=Honorary Professor: Chris Oliver |publisher=University of Edinburgh|date=16 October 2015|accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, along with other academics, he signed a letter to the [[Medical Schools Council]] and the [[General Medical Council]] to highlight the lack of lifestyle education in undergraduate medical curricula across the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/oct/19/doctors-know-too-little-about-effects-of-nutrition-and-exercise|title=Doctors 'know too little about nutrition and exercise'|last=Campbell|first=Denis|date=19 October 2016|work=The Guardian |access-date=9 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/future-doctors-need-training-on-exercise-and-nutrition-1-4263169|title=Future doctors need training on exercise and nutrition.|last=Buchan|first=Lizzy|date=19 October 2016|work=The Scotsman|access-date=9 December 2017}}</ref> \n\nHe is on the board of the charities Mobile International Surgical Teams (MiST).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mistngo.co.uk/about-us |title=About us |website=mistngo.co.uk|accessdate=10 December 2017}}</ref>, Scottish Men's Shed Association <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scottishmsa.org.uk/board-of-trustees/|title=Board of Trustees|website=Scottish Men's Sheds Association|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> ,Edinburgh and Lothians Greenspace Trust <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elgt.org.uk/about-us/board/|title=About us > Staff board|last=|first=|date=|website=www.elgt.org.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref>, Drugs, Alcohol and Psychotherapies Ltd (DAPL) <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dapl.net/about/the-team/|title=About > the team |website=www.dapl.net|access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Published work ==\nOliver claims to have authored over 400 publications and presentations. He written about [[Health informatics|medical informatics]], assessment in [[Medical education in the United Kingdom|medical education,]] physical activity and orthopaedic surgery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Chris_Oliver9|title=Christopher W Oliver (The University of Edinburgh, Edinburgh) on ResearchGate - Expertise: Teacher Education, Curriculum Theory, Adult Education|work=researchgate.net}}</ref><ref name=\"ORCID\">{{cite web|url=http://orcid.org/0000-0003-1331-6429|title=Prof Christopher W Oliver (0000-0003-1331-6429) - ORCID - Connecting Research and Researchers|work=orcid.org|accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was a section editor in the multi-author [[Trauma surgery|major trauma]] section of \"Oxford Textbook of Fundamentals of Surgery\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Oxford Textbook of Fundamentals of Surgery|last1=Thomas|first1=William |first2=Malcolm W. R. |last2=Reed |first3=Michael G. |last3=Wyatt |publisher=Oxford University Press|year=July 2016|isbn=978-0199665549|location=United Kingdom|pages=|doi=10.1093/med/9780199665549.001.0001}}</ref> published in July 2016.\n\n== Personal life ==\nOliver gained excessive weight during his adult life and at his heaviest was 171 kg (27 stone). In February 2007 he had a [[Adjustable gastric band|LapBand]] fitted laparascopically and by 2011 his weight reduced to 102 kg (12 stone).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/tipping-the-scales-edinburgh-surgeon-fights-off-super-obesity-1-1587236 |title=Tipping the scales: Edinburgh surgeon fights off 'super-obesity' |work=The Scotsman |date=14 April 2011|access-date=9 December 2017}}</ref> In 2014 the band snapped and it was later removed.<ref>{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=The Road to Fitness|url=https://www.research.ed.ac.uk/portal/en/activities/prof-chris-oliver-discusses-the-road-to-fitness-his-journey-from-obese-burnt-out-consultant-to-health-and-well-being-advocate(c7bbf3ec-6f3b-437a-83d8-2ac4d2a2e5fb).html|journal=Surgeon's News|publisher=Royal College of Surgeons Edinburgh|volume=|issue=September 2017|pages=34\u201335|via=}}</ref>\n\nOliver is an avid endurance [[Cycling|cyclist]]. In 2013 he cycled 3415 miles from Los Angeles to Boston, USA with his daughter Catherine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/bike-blog/2013/jul/18/los-angeles-boston-united-states-rockies-bike-blog|title=From Los Angeles to Boston: an epic ride across the United States|first=Chris|last=Oliver|date=18 July 2013|publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=10 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://cyclingsurgeon.bike/}}\n* [http://www.research.ed.ac.uk/portal/en/persons/chris-oliver(4d8f0274-4cb1-4333-9ef1-e8e282d053b2).html profile] at University of Edinburgh Research Explorer\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oliver, Chris}}\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish surgeons]]\n[[Category:Scottish scholars and academics]]\n[[Category:People from Forest Gate]]\n[[Category:21st-century Scottish medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal College of Surgeons of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:British orthopaedic surgeons]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   = Professor\n| name               = Christopher William Oliver\n| honorific_suffix   =\n| image              = Professor-Chris-Oliver.jpg\n| birth_date         =\n| birth_place        = Forest Gate, London, England\n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| occupation         = Surgeon\n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| alma_mater         = [[University College Hospital]], [[University College London]]\n| workplaces         = [[University of Edinburgh]], [[Napier University]]\n| website            = https://cyclingsurgeon.bike/\n}}\n\n'''Chris Oliver''' Edinburgh orthopaedic surgeon/professor. King James IV Professor Royal College of Surgeons of Edinburgh 2019-20<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rcsed.ac.uk/professional-support-development-resources/grants-jobs-and-placements/research-travel-and-award-opportunities/awards-and-medals|title=Awards and Medals {{!}} The Royal College of Surgeons of Edinburgh|work=The Royal College of Surgeons of Edinburgh|access-date=2018-09-29|language=en}}</ref>. Associate Research Fellow, School of Engineering and Built Environment, [[Transport Research Institute]], Edinburgh Napier University 2018-<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.napier.ac.uk/tri/2019/02/04/chris-oliver-appointed-associate-research-fellow-at-tri/|title=Chris Oliver - appointed Associate Research Fellow at TRI|last=yvonnelawrie|date=2019-02-04|website=Transport Research Institute|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref>. Honorary [[Professor]] in Physical Activity for Health at the [[Moray House School of Education|Physical Activity for Health Research Centre]], [[University of Edinburgh]] 2015-2018.<ref name=\"PAHRC ed.ac.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.research.ed.ac.uk/portal/en/persons/chris-oliver(4d8f0274-4cb1-4333-9ef1-e8e282d053b2).html|title=Chris Oliver, University of Edinburgh Research Explorer|last=|first=|date=|website=Univeristy of Edinburgh|publisher=University of Edinburgh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref> Consultant Trauma [[Orthopedic surgery|Orthopaedic]] and Hand Surgeon at [[Royal Infirmary of Edinburgh]] 1997-2017.\n\n==Education==\nIn 1992, Oliver completed a doctorate ([[Doctor of Medicine|MD]]) from [[University College London]] in spinal muscle physiology and artificial intelligence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.research.ed.ac.uk/portal/en/publications/development-of-surface-electromyographic-spectral-analysis-techniques-for-assessing-paraspinal-muscle-function(74669c81-eb8d-4aa8-abff-f78e3e20844e).html|title= Edinburgh Research Explorer: Development of surface electromyographic spectral analysis techniques for assessing paraspinal muscle function |publisher=www.research.ed.ac.uk|accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nOliver retired in 2018 from the [[Royal Infirmary of Edinburgh]] as a Consultant Trauma Orthopaedic Surgeon in the Department of Trauma and Orthopaedics, [[University of Edinburgh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ed.ac.uk/clinical-sciences/orthopaedics-trauma/staff/consultants|title=Department of Orthopaedics and Trauma - The University of Edinburgh|website=ed.ac.uk  |date=18 July 2016|accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref> Career was profiled by the British Medical Journal, Careers  in July 2018<ref>{{Cite journal|last=O\u2019Dowd|first=Adrian|date=2018-05-31|title=Chris Oliver: from orthopaedic surgeon to fitness professor|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/361/bmj.k1768|journal=BMJ|language=en|volume=361|pages=k1768|doi=10.1136/bmj.k1768|issn=0959-8138|pmid=29853632|doi-access=free}}</ref>.\n\nBetween 2015-2018 he was honorary Professor of Physical Activity for Health to [[Moray House School of Education|Physical Activity for Health Research Centre (PAHRC)]] at the [[University of Edinburgh]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.ed.ac.uk/news/staff/appointments-awards/2015/chris-oliver-120615|title=Honorary Professor: Chris Oliver |publisher=University of Edinburgh|date=16 October 2015|accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, along with other academics, he signed a letter to the [[Medical Schools Council]] and the [[General Medical Council]] to highlight the lack of lifestyle education in undergraduate medical curricula across the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/oct/19/doctors-know-too-little-about-effects-of-nutrition-and-exercise|title=Doctors 'know too little about nutrition and exercise'|last=Campbell|first=Denis|date=19 October 2016|work=The Guardian |access-date=9 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/future-doctors-need-training-on-exercise-and-nutrition-1-4263169|title=Future doctors need training on exercise and nutrition.|last=Buchan|first=Lizzy|date=19 October 2016|work=The Scotsman|access-date=9 December 2017}}</ref> \n\nHe is on the board of the charities Mobile International Surgical Teams (MiST).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mistngo.co.uk/about-us |title=About us |website=mistngo.co.uk|accessdate=10 December 2017}}</ref>, Edinburgh and Lothians Greenspace Trust <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elgt.org.uk/about-us/board/|title=About us > Staff board|last=|first=|date=|website=www.elgt.org.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref>, Drugs, Alcohol and Psychotherapies Ltd (DAPL) <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dapl.net/about/the-team/|title=About > the team |website=www.dapl.net|access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Published work ==\nOliver claims to have authored over 400 publications and presentations. He written about [[Health informatics|medical informatics]], assessment in [[Medical education in the United Kingdom|medical education,]] physical activity and orthopaedic surgery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Chris_Oliver9|title=Christopher W Oliver (The University of Edinburgh, Edinburgh) on ResearchGate - Expertise: Teacher Education, Curriculum Theory, Adult Education|work=researchgate.net}}</ref><ref name=\"ORCID\">{{cite web|url=http://orcid.org/0000-0003-1331-6429|title=Prof Christopher W Oliver (0000-0003-1331-6429) - ORCID - Connecting Research and Researchers|work=orcid.org|accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was a section editor in the multi-author [[Trauma surgery|major trauma]] section of \"Oxford Textbook of Fundamentals of Surgery\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Oxford Textbook of Fundamentals of Surgery|last1=Thomas|first1=William |first2=Malcolm W. R. |last2=Reed |first3=Michael G. |last3=Wyatt |publisher=Oxford University Press|year=July 2016|isbn=978-0199665549|location=United Kingdom|pages=|doi=10.1093/med/9780199665549.001.0001}}</ref> published in July 2016.\n\n== Personal life ==\nOliver gained excessive weight during his adult life and at his heaviest was 171 kg (27 stone). In February 2007 he had a [[Adjustable gastric band|LapBand]] fitted laparascopically and by 2011 his weight reduced to 102 kg (12 stone).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/tipping-the-scales-edinburgh-surgeon-fights-off-super-obesity-1-1587236 |title=Tipping the scales: Edinburgh surgeon fights off 'super-obesity' |work=The Scotsman |date=14 April 2011|access-date=9 December 2017}}</ref> In 2014 the band snapped and it was later removed.<ref>{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=The Road to Fitness|url=https://www.research.ed.ac.uk/portal/en/activities/prof-chris-oliver-discusses-the-road-to-fitness-his-journey-from-obese-burnt-out-consultant-to-health-and-well-being-advocate(c7bbf3ec-6f3b-437a-83d8-2ac4d2a2e5fb).html|journal=Surgeon's News|publisher=Royal College of Surgeons Edinburgh|volume=|issue=September 2017|pages=34\u201335|via=}}</ref>\n\nOliver is an avid endurance [[Cycling|cyclist]]. In 2013 he cycled 3415 miles from Los Angeles to Boston, USA with his daughter Catherine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/bike-blog/2013/jul/18/los-angeles-boston-united-states-rockies-bike-blog|title=From Los Angeles to Boston: an epic ride across the United States|first=Chris|last=Oliver|date=18 July 2013|publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=10 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://cyclingsurgeon.bike/}}\n* [http://www.research.ed.ac.uk/portal/en/persons/chris-oliver(4d8f0274-4cb1-4333-9ef1-e8e282d053b2).html profile] at University of Edinburgh Research Explorer\n\n{{