{"title_page": "Paktor", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=March 2016}}\n{{advert|date=March 2016}}\n{{notability|Companies|date=March 2016}}\n{{Orphan|date=March 2016}}\n}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox software\n| title            = Paktor\n| name             = Paktor\n| logo             = LogoPaktor.png\n| developer        = [[Paktor Pte Ltd]]\n| released         = {{Start date|2013|6|}}\n| operating system = [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n| website          = {{URL|https://gopaktor.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Paktor''' is a location-based [[dating]] and networking [[mobile app]]lication that connects mutually interested users and allows them to chat individually or as a group. Founded in [[Singapore]], the app was launched in June 2013..,<ref name=Techinasia>{{cite news |url=https://www.techinasia.com/paktor-series-b-funding |publisher=TechInAsia |title=Singapore\u2019s Paktor gets $7.3M to become more than a dating app}}</ref> and has over 5 billion swipes to date (October 2015).<ref name=Marketing>{{cite news |url=http://www.marketing-interactive.com/local-tinder-like-app-paktor-draws-another-sg10mln-funding |publisher=Marketing Interactive |title=Local Tinder-like app Paktor draws another SG$10 mil in funding}}</ref>  In late 2013, Paktor launched a subsidiary called GaiGai, an offline dating service that focuses on matching-making and dating events. The word 'Paktor' originates from the Cantonese word for 'dating' (Chinese character \u62cd\u62d6).<ref>The jocular [[Singlish]] word ''paktorlogy'' refers to the \"science of going on a date with someone\", see p. 106 in [[Ghil'ad Zuckermann]] (2003), [[Language Contact and Lexical Enrichment in Israeli Hebrew]], Houndmills: [[Palgrave Macmillan]], (Palgrave Studies in Language History and Language Change, Series editor: Charles Jones). {{ISBN|1-4039-1723-X}}.</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Founding ===\nPaktor was founded by Joseph Phua and Ng Jing Shen.<ref name=Crunchbase>{{cite news |url=https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/paktor#/entity |publisher=CrunchBase |title=Paktor}}</ref>\n\nPaktor was first launched in Singapore in June 2013, when online and mobile dating was still in its infancy in Asia. Despite the immature market, there was a lot of interest from consumers and according to a Paktor newsletter, there were 250000 matches in the first 2 weeks of 2014 making Paktor the #1 social networking app for singles in Asia.<ref name=Vulcan>{{cite news |url=https://vulcanpost.com/4199/dating-app-paktor-hooks-up-250000-singles-in-two-weeks |publisher=Vulcan Post |title=Dating app Paktor hooks up 250000 singles in two weeks }}</ref> The company also shared that it had received over 100 million profile ratings at that time.\n\nThe app is also available in [[Taiwan]],<ref name=\"Apple\">{{cite news |url=http://www.appledaily.com.tw/realtimenews/article/new/20131031/284260 |publisher=Apple Daily |title=\u4ea4\u53cbapp\u4e0a\u5e02\u3000\u502a\u5b89\u6771\u628a\u59b9\u7121\u570b\u754c}}</ref> [[Malaysia]], [[Indonesia]],<ref name=\"Daily\">{{cite news |url=http://en.dailysocial.id/post/paktor-is-officially-launched-in-indonesia |publisher=Daily Social |title=Paktor is Officially Launched in Indonesia}}</ref> [[Vietnam]], [[Thailand]], and [[South Korea]].\n\n=== Change of Management ===\nIn November 2017, Paktor Group appointed co-founder and chief technology officer Ng Jing Shen as CEO of Paktor Group, taking over from current CEO Joseph Phua. Phua will remain the group CEO of M17 Entertainment which was formed after the merger of Paktor and 17 Media. The company also promoted current head of operations Shn Juay to Chief Operating Officer at Paktor Group.<ref name=MarketingInteractive>{{cite news |url=http://www.marketing-interactive.com/dating-app-paktor-names-ceo/ |publisher=Marketing Interactive |title=Dating app Paktor names new CEO and COO}}</ref>\n\n== Company Overview ==\n\n=== Financials ===\nIn March 2014, Paktor revealed its first round of [[funding]] with a US$500,000 pre-Series-A round that valued the brand at US$6.5 million.<ref name=\"Tech2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.techinasia.com/dating-app-paktor-raises-500000-number-parts-asia |publisher=TechInAsia |title=Dating app Paktor raises $500,000, says it\u2019s number one in parts of Asia}}</ref> At this time, co-founder and CEO Joseph Phua was quoted as saying that the app was \u201ceasily 10-20 times ahead of the next player\u201d<ref name=\"e27\">{{cite news |url=http://e27.co/dating-app-paktor-raises-us500k-valuation-set-us6-5m |publisher=e27 |title=Dating app Paktor raises US$500K with valuation set at US$6.5M}}</ref> referring to their main markets; Singapore, Malaysia, Vietnam, Thailand, Taiwan and the Philippines.\n\nSeries A was secured in November 2014, bringing the total raised to US$5 million.<ref name=\"Deal\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dealstreetasia.com/stories/dating-app-paktor-raises-5m-series-a-funding-907 |publisher=DealStreetAsia |title=Dating app Paktor raises $3.3m Series A funding}}</ref> This round was led by Vertex Ventures Southeast Asia & India. The funds were reported to be used for expansion into different territories and the introduction of new services under the Paktor group. At this time, the size of the network stood at 1.5 million registered users.<ref name=\"Deal\"/>\n\nThe next milestone was the US$7.3 million Series B funding in July 2015. This raised total funding to more than US$12 million and Paktor said its network had five million registered users and 12 million matches a month.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.techinasia.com/paktor-series-b-funding |publisher=TechInAsia |title=Singapore\u2019s Paktor gets $7.3M to become more than a dating app}}</ref> There were also 500 million monthly swipes on average across the region.<ref name=\"CNA\">{{cite news |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/business/singapore/dating-app-paktor/1981750.html |publisher=Channel NewsAsia |title=Dating app Paktor receives S$10 million in latest funding round}}</ref>\n\nThe startup secured another US$10 million in a venture round with its sights set on expansion in Japan and South Korea. YJ Capital \u2014 the corporate venture firm belonging to Yahoo Capital \u2014 led the round, which included participation from fellow new investors Global Grand Leisure, Golden Equator Capital and Sebrina Holdings, as well as existing backers Vertex Ventures Southeast Asia & India, MNC Media Group, Majuven and [[Convergence Ventures]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/07/11/asian-tinder-rival-paktor-lands-10m-to-further-global-push-with-japan-and-korea-launches/|title=Asian Tinder rival Paktor lands $10M to further global push with launches in Japan and South Korea|last=Russell|first=Jon|website=TechCrunch|access-date=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Paktor announced another round of funding in the amount of $32.5 million to expand its focus into new kinds of mobile entertainment. This new raise, was led by U.S.-Asia-based K2 Global and Indonesia\u2019s MNC Media Group, with participation from other, undisclosed investors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/10/31/paktor/|title=Asia-focused dating app Paktor lands $32.5M to push into \u2018social entertainment\u2019|last=Russell|first=Jon|website=TechCrunch}}</ref>\n\nIn December the same year, the company announced that it has agreed to buy a controlling stake in Taiwanese start-up 17 Media. 17 Media owns a photo-sharing and live streaming app that has over 15 million users worldwide. The deal was Paktor's first acquisition and comes as the start-up looks to diversify into the social entertainment space.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/business/dating-app-paktor-moves-into-social-entertainment-with-first-acq-7637236/|title=Dating app Paktor moves into social entertainment with first acquisition|last=Tang|first=See Kit|website=ChannelNewsAsia}}</ref>\n\nPaktor announced its next wave of acquisitions in February 2017 with Down, Kickoff, Goodnight and Groopify joining the group and forming the Paktor Labs Division. Paktor Labs will act as an accelerator for social apps with high potential.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://vulcanpost.com/602421/paktor-labs-acquisition-accelerator/ |publisher=Vulcanpost |title=Paktor Acquires 3 Other Dating App Startups, Sets Up What Might Be The World's First Dating Lab}}</ref> The dating app next announced its merger with 17 Media, forming a new company called M17 Entertainment and combining all assets and revenue under the new entity.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/04/26/paktor-merges-with-taiwans-17-media/ |publisher=TechCrunch |title=Paktor, a major rival to Tinder in Asia, moves into live-streaming via merger deal}}</ref>\n\n=== Advertising ===\nIn 2015, the app appointed Taiwanese actress and social media personality, Ouyang Nini,<ref name=\"WOW\">{{cite news |url=http://www.wownews.tw/article.php?sn=25435 |publisher=WOW! News |title=\u570b\u6c11\u751c\u5fc3\u6b50\u967d\u59ae\u59ae\u4ee3\u8a00\u4e9e\u6d32\u7b2c\u4e00\u5927\u4ea4\u53cbAPP\u2013Paktor\u62cd\u62d6}}</ref>  and Indonesian actor, Junior Liem,<ref name=\"Inponsel\">{{cite news |url=http://www.inponsel.co.id/berita/d/337715/ganteng-dan-tidak-playboy-aplikasi-kencan-ini-memilih-junior-liem-jadi-brand-ambassador |publisher=Inponsel |title=\nGanteng dan Tidak Playboy, Aplikasi Kencan Ini Memilih Junior Liem Jadi Brand Ambassador}}</ref>   as the brand\u2019s ambassadors in Taiwan and Indonesia respectively. A series of visual advertisements<ref name=\"Youtube\">{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j7TepPiePBg|publisher=Paktor ID|title=TVC Paktor Indonesia}}</ref>  were launched with the appointment announcement. At a press conference, Ouyang Nini said that her father, former actor and Chinese Nationalist Party (KMT) Taipei City Councilor, Ouyang Lung,<ref name=\"Taipei\">{{cite news |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2014/11/08/2003603954 |publisher=Taipei Times |title=2014 ELECTIONS: Photogenic aides, relatives giving a boost to candidates}}</ref> approves of her endorsement to use the app to meet new friends.<ref name=\"Apple2\">{{cite news |url=http://www.appledaily.com.tw/realtimenews/article/new/20150415/592995/ |publisher=Apple Daily |title=\u8001\u7238\u5f88\u958b\u660e\uff01 \u6b50\u967d\u59ae\u59ae\u53ef\u4ee5\u7db2\u4ea4\u60f9}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== In the region ===\n\nBeyond Singapore, Paktor is available in Taiwan,<ref name=\"Apple\"/> Malaysia, Indonesia,<ref name=\"Daily\"/> Vietnam and Thailand.\n\nAs of September 2016, an estimated 12 million people in Southeast Asia use the app every month, with an average of 20 million matches per month and over 5 billion swipes to date.<ref name=\"Marketing\"/> There are an estimated 500,000 users in Indonesia alone.<ref name=Avatar>{{cite news |url=http://it.avatar-nusantara.com/2015/04/10/aplikasi-paktor-klaim-miliki-500-ribu-pengguna-di-indonesia |publisher=Avatar Nusantara Technologies |title=Aplikasi Paktor Klaim Miliki 500 Ribu Pengguna di Indonesia}}</ref>\n\nThe app has its own localised slogan in Taiwan, \"\u53cb\u59b3\u9078\u64c7 \u53cb\u4f60\u9078\u64c7\", which means \u2018to choose your friend yourself\u2019.<ref name=Sogi>{{cite news |url=http://www.sogi.com.tw/articles/%E4%BA%9E%E6%B4%B2%E4%BA%A4%E5%8F%8B%E8%BB%9F%E9%AB%94%E9%A0%98%E5%B0%8E%E5%93%81%E7%89%8C_Paktor%E5%85%A8%E6%96%B0%E6%94%B9%E7%89%88_%E4%B8%A6%E9%A6%96%E5%89%B5%E3%80%8C%E5%84%AA%E8%B3%AA%E6%8B%8D%E5%8F%8B%E5%85%AC%E7%B4%84%E3%80%8D/6236821 |publisher=Sogi |title=\u4e9e\u6d32\u4ea4\u53cb\u8edf\u9ad4\u9818\u5c0e\u54c1\u724c Paktor\u5168\u65b0\u6539\u7248 \u4e26\u9996\u5275\u300c\u512a\u8cea\u62cd\u53cb\u516c\u7d04 }}</ref> In January 2015, Paktor created two eye-catching telephone booths near Taipei\u2019s iconic landmark, the Taipei 101, to encourage passers-by to explore the app and provide assurance that the app is a safe and private way to meet new friends across countries<ref name=Damanwoo>{{cite news |url=http://www.damanwoo.com/node/85837 |publisher=Damanwoo |title=\u5728101\u898b\u8b49\u4e0b\u4f86\u5834\u611b\u7684\u9023\u7dda\uff01\u6d6a\u6f2b Paktor \u96fb\u8a71\u4ead\u88dd\u7f6e}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Paktor set a Guinness World record for The World\u2019s Largest Speed Dating Event held in Vietnam.<ref name=PRnews>{{cite news |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/paktor--sagiko-present-a-guinness-world-records-record-attempt---paktor-speed-date-night---the-worlds-largest-speed-dating-event-233023661.html |publisher=PR Newswire |title=Paktor & Sagiko Present A Guinness World Records Record Attempt - Paktor Speed Date Night - The World's Largest Speed Dating Event}}</ref> The event drew 600 participants including local celebrities popular among Vietnamese youth. This record was most recently broken by Calgary Speed Dating Inc. (Canada) at Telus Spark Science Centre in Calgary, Canada, on 14 February 2014<ref name=Guinness>{{cite news |url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/largest-speed-dating-event |publisher=Guinness World Records |title=Largest speed dating event}}</ref>\n\n=== In the media ===\n\nPaktor has received widespread news coverage and been featured on TechCrunch,<ref name=Techcrunch>{{cite news |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/11/17/with-5m-in-funding-tinder-like-paktor-wants-to-get-southeast-asia-using-dating-apps |publisher=TechCrunch |title=With $5M In Funding, Tinder-Like Paktor Wants To Get Southeast Asia Using Dating Apps}}</ref> Bloomberg,<ref name=Bloomberg>{{cite news |url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/money/video/finding-the-perfect-match-on-mobile/vp-AA9UFNl |publisher=Bloomberg |title=Finding the Perfect Match on Mobile}}</ref> CNBC Asia,<ref name=CNBC>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2014/08/29/singapore-entrepreneur-turns-heartache-into-cash.html |publisher=CNBC Asia |title=Singapore entrepreneur turns heartache into cash}}</ref> CNN<ref name=CNN>{{cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/03/22/technology/asia-dating-apps-tinder |publisher=CNN |title=4 ways Asian dating apps are anti-Tinder}}</ref>  and others. The app was positively received in Singapore when it was launched gaining over 25,000 users in the first month.<ref name=Tech3>{{cite news |url=https://www.techinasia.com/paktor |publisher=TechInAsia |title=From heartbreak to Paktor, and how the mobile dating app craze is sweeping across Asia}}</ref> There were also comparisons to established mobile dating apps like Tinder and how it was a similar product and had the same mechanics.\n\nGlobal Dating Insights (GDI) publication regarded Paktor as one of the dating apps to watch. With relatively little competition in Southeast Asia, GDI assesses that the app to have huge potential, crediting the CEO for having \u2018expertly navigated\u2019 the Southeast Asian market with multiple countries each with different cultures, dating habits and languages. \nIn October 2015, Paktor hired two former Meetic senior marketing executives, Jose Ruano and Miguel Mangas, spearheading overseas expansion efforts outside of Asia. The two speak Spanish, which has strategic global importance as 425 million people in the world use Spanish as their first language. Already available in the two most spoken languages, English and Chinese, the hiring acquisitions would allow Paktor to break into European and South American markets.<ref name=GDI>{{cite news |url=http://globaldatinginsights.com/2016/02/12/gdi-dating-industry-power-book-2016-is-now-live/  |publisher=Global Dating Insights |title=Global Dating Insights Power Book 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe conservative nature of Asian cultures has also presented challenges, where regular dating and casual sex is frowned upon.<ref name=Straits>{{cite news |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/no-hanky-panky-dating-apps-woo-investors-with-local-expertise  |publisher=The Straits Times |title=No hanky panky: Dating apps woo investors with local expertise}}</ref>\n\n=== Concerns ===\nIn 2015, a Reddit post highlighted the vulnerability of the GaiGai website due to the lack of security encryptions<ref name=Reddit>{{cite news |url=https://www.reddit.com/r/singapore/comments/32mxlt/psa_do_not_use_gaigai_website_paktors_offline |publisher=Reddit |title=PSA: Do NOT use GaiGai website (Paktor's offline dating service)}}</ref> GaiGai responded that it has since added SSL/TLS encryption. However, some Reddit users commented that more layers of encryption are necessary in order to provide better security for the clientele database. Paktor and GaiGai have since updated their privacy and data protection policy in August 2015<ref name=Paktor>{{cite news |url=http://www.gopaktor.com/#/privacy |publisher=Paktor |title=Privacy Policy)}}</ref><ref name=GaiGai>{{cite news |url=https://letsgaigai.com/#/privacy |publisher=GaiGai |title=Privacy and Data Protection Policy)}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|https://gopaktor.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Mobile social software]]\n[[Category:Geosocial networking]]\n[[Category:Online dating services of Singapore]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=March 2016}}\n{{advert|date=March 2016}}\n{{notability|Companies|date=March 2016}}\n{{Orphan|date=March 2016}}\n}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox software\n| title            = Paktor\n| name             = Paktor\n| logo             = LogoPaktor.png\n| developer        = [[Paktor Pte Ltd]]\n| released         = {{Start date|2013|6|}}\n| operating system = [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n| website          = {{URL|https://gopaktor.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Paktor''' is a location-based [[dating]] and networking [[mobile app]]lication that connects mutually interested users and allows them to chat individually or as a group. Founded in [[Singapore]], the app was launched in June 2013..,<ref name=Techinasia>{{cite news |url=https://www.techinasia.com/paktor-series-b-funding |publisher=TechInAsia |title=Singapore\u2019s Paktor gets $7.3M to become more than a dating app}}</ref> and has over 5 billion swipes to date (October 2015).<ref name=Marketing>{{cite news |url=http://www.marketing-interactive.com/local-tinder-like-app-paktor-draws-another-sg10mln-funding |publisher=Marketing Interactive |title=Local Tinder-like app Paktor draws another SG$10 mil in funding}}</ref>  In late 2013, Paktor launched a subsidiary called GaiGai, an offline dating service that focuses on matching-making and dating events. The word 'Paktor' originates from the Cantonese word for 'dating' (Chinese character \u62cd\u62d6).<ref>The jocular [[Singlish]] word ''paktorlogy'' refers to the \"science of going on a date with someone\", see p. 106 in [[Ghil'ad Zuckermann]] (2003), [[Language Contact and Lexical Enrichment in Israeli Hebrew]], Houndmills: [[Palgrave Macmillan]], (Palgrave Studies in Language History and Language Change, Series editor: Charles Jones). {{ISBN|1-4039-1723-X}}.</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Founding ===\nPaktor was founded by Joseph Phua and Ng Jing Shen.<ref name=Crunchbase>{{cite news |url=https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/paktor#/entity |publisher=CrunchBase |title=Paktor}}</ref>\n\nPaktor was first launched in Singapore in June 2013, when online and mobile dating was still in its infancy in Asia. Despite the immature market, there was a lot of interest from consumers and according to a Paktor newsletter, there were 250000 matches in the first 2 weeks of 2014 making Paktor the #1 social networking app for singles in Asia.<ref name=Vulcan>{{cite news |url=https://vulcanpost.com/4199/dating-app-paktor-hooks-up-250000-singles-in-two-weeks |publisher=Vulcan Post |title=Dating app Paktor hooks up 250000 singles in two weeks }}</ref> The company also shared that it had received over 100 million profile ratings at that time.\n\nThe app is also available in [[Taiwan]],<ref name=\"Apple\">{{cite news |url=http://www.appledaily.com.tw/realtimenews/article/new/20131031/284260 |publisher=Apple Daily |title=\u4ea4\u53cbapp\u4e0a\u5e02\u3000\u502a\u5b89\u6771\u628a\u59b9\u7121\u570b\u754c}}</ref> [[Malaysia]], [[Indonesia]],<ref name=\"Daily\">{{cite news |url=http://en.dailysocial.id/post/paktor-is-officially-launched-in-indonesia |publisher=Daily Social |title=Paktor is Officially Launched in Indonesia}}</ref> [[Vietnam]], [[Thailand]], and [[South Korea]].\n\n=== Change of Management ===\nIn November 2017, Paktor Group appointed co-founder and chief technology officer Ng Jing Shen as CEO of Paktor Group, taking over from current CEO Joseph Phua. Phua will remain the group CEO of M17 Entertainment which was formed after the merger of Paktor and 17 Media. The company also promoted current head of operations Shn Juay to Chief Operating Officer at Paktor Group.<ref name=MarketingInteractive>{{cite news |url=http://www.marketing-interactive.com/dating-app-paktor-names-ceo/ |publisher=Marketing Interactive |title=Dating app Paktor names new CEO and COO}}</ref>\n\n== Company Overview ==\n\n=== Financials ===\nIn March 2014, Paktor revealed its first round of [[funding]] with a US$500,000 pre-Series-A round that valued the brand at US$6.5 million.<ref name=\"Tech2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.techinasia.com/dating-app-paktor-raises-500000-number-parts-asia |publisher=TechInAsia |title=Dating app Paktor raises $500,000, says it\u2019s number one in parts of Asia}}</ref> At this time, co-founder and CEO Joseph Phua was quoted as saying that the app was \u201ceasily 10-20 times ahead of the next player\u201d<ref name=\"e27\">{{cite news |url=http://e27.co/dating-app-paktor-raises-us500k-valuation-set-us6-5m |publisher=e27 |title=Dating app Paktor raises US$500K with valuation set at US$6.5M}}</ref> referring to their main markets; Singapore, Malaysia, Vietnam, Thailand, Taiwan and the Philippines.\n\nSeries A was secured in November 2014, bringing the total raised to US$5 million.<ref name=\"Deal\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dealstreetasia.com/stories/dating-app-paktor-raises-5m-series-a-funding-907 |publisher=DealStreetAsia |title=Dating app Paktor raises $3.3m Series A funding}}</ref> This round was led by Vertex Ventures, a subsidiary of Singapore\u2019s [[Temasek Holdings]]. The funds were reported to be used for expansion into different territories and the introduction of new services under the Paktor group. At this time, the size of the network stood at 1.5 million registered users.<ref name=\"Deal\"/>\n\nThe next milestone was the US$7.3 million Series B funding in July 2015. This raised total funding to more than US$12 million and Paktor said its network had five million registered users and 12 million matches a month.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.techinasia.com/paktor-series-b-funding |publisher=TechInAsia |title=Singapore\u2019s Paktor gets $7.3M to become more than a dating app}}</ref> There were also 500 million monthly swipes on average across the region.<ref name=\"CNA\">{{cite news |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/business/singapore/dating-app-paktor/1981750.html |publisher=Channel NewsAsia |title=Dating app Paktor receives S$10 million in latest funding round}}</ref>\n\nThe startup secured another US$10 million in a venture round with its sights set on expansion in Japan and South Korea. YJ Capital \u2014 the corporate venture firm belonging to Yahoo Capital \u2014 led the round, which included participation from fellow new investors Global Grand Leisure, Golden Equator Capital and Sebrina Holdings, as well as existing backers Vertex Ventures (which belongs to Singapore sovereign wealth fund Temasek) MNC Media Group, Majuven and [[Convergence Ventures]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/07/11/asian-tinder-rival-paktor-lands-10m-to-further-global-push-with-japan-and-korea-launches/|title=Asian Tinder rival Paktor lands $10M to further global push with launches in Japan and South Korea|last=Russell|first=Jon|website=TechCrunch|access-date=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Paktor announced another round of funding in the amount of $32.5 million to expand its focus into new kinds of mobile entertainment. This new raise, was led by U.S.-Asia-based K2 Global and Indonesia\u2019s MNC Media Group, with participation from other, undisclosed investors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/10/31/paktor/|title=Asia-focused dating app Paktor lands $32.5M to push into \u2018social entertainment\u2019|last=Russell|first=Jon|website=TechCrunch}}</ref>\n\nIn December the same year, the company announced that it has agreed to buy a controlling stake in Taiwanese start-up 17 Media. 17 Media owns a photo-sharing and live streaming app that has over 15 million users worldwide. The deal was Paktor's first acquisition and comes as the start-up looks to diversify into the social entertainment space.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/business/dating-app-paktor-moves-into-social-entertainment-with-first-acq-7637236/|title=Dating app Paktor moves into social entertainment with first acquisition|last=Tang|first=See Kit|website=ChannelNewsAsia}}</ref>\n\nPaktor announced its next wave of acquisitions in February 2017 with Down, Kickoff, Goodnight and Groopify joining the group and forming the Paktor Labs Division. Paktor Labs will act as an accelerator for social apps with high potential.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://vulcanpost.com/602421/paktor-labs-acquisition-accelerator/ |publisher=Vulcanpost |title=Paktor Acquires 3 Other Dating App Startups, Sets Up What Might Be The World's First Dating Lab}}</ref> The dating app next announced its merger with 17 Media, forming a new company called M17 Entertainment and combining all assets and revenue under the new entity.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/04/26/paktor-merges-with-taiwans-17-media/ |publisher=TechCrunch |title=Paktor, a major rival to Tinder in Asia, moves into live-streaming via merger deal}}</ref>\n\n=== Advertising ===\nIn 2015, the app appointed Taiwanese actress and social media personality, Ouyang Nini,<ref name=\"WOW\">{{cite news |url=http://www.wownews.tw/article.php?sn=25435 |publisher=WOW! News |title=\u570b\u6c11\u751c\u5fc3\u6b50\u967d\u59ae\u59ae\u4ee3\u8a00\u4e9e\u6d32\u7b2c\u4e00\u5927\u4ea4\u53cbAPP\u2013Paktor\u62cd\u62d6}}</ref>  and Indonesian actor, Junior Liem,<ref name=\"Inponsel\">{{cite news |url=http://www.inponsel.co.id/berita/d/337715/ganteng-dan-tidak-playboy-aplikasi-kencan-ini-memilih-junior-liem-jadi-brand-ambassador |publisher=Inponsel |title=\nGanteng dan Tidak Playboy, Aplikasi Kencan Ini Memilih Junior Liem Jadi Brand Ambassador}}</ref>   as the brand\u2019s ambassadors in Taiwan and Indonesia respectively. A series of visual advertisements<ref name=\"Youtube\">{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j7TepPiePBg|publisher=Paktor ID|title=TVC Paktor Indonesia}}</ref>  were launched with the appointment announcement. At a press conference, Ouyang Nini said that her father, former actor and Chinese Nationalist Party (KMT) Taipei City Councilor, Ouyang Lung,<ref name=\"Taipei\">{{cite news |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2014/11/08/2003603954 |publisher=Taipei Times |title=2014 ELECTIONS: Photogenic aides, relatives giving a boost to candidates}}</ref> approves of her endorsement to use the app to meet new friends.<ref name=\"Apple2\">{{cite news |url=http://www.appledaily.com.tw/realtimenews/article/new/20150415/592995/ |publisher=Apple Daily |title=\u8001\u7238\u5f88\u958b\u660e\uff01 \u6b50\u967d\u59ae\u59ae\u53ef\u4ee5\u7db2\u4ea4\u60f9}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== In the region ===\n\nBeyond Singapore, Paktor is available in Taiwan,<ref name=\"Apple\"/> Malaysia, Indonesia,<ref name=\"Daily\"/> Vietnam and Thailand.\n\nAs of September 2016, an estimated 12 million people in Southeast Asia use the app every month, with an average of 20 million matches per month and over 5 billion swipes to date.<ref name=\"Marketing\"/> There are an estimated 500,000 users in Indonesia alone.<ref name=Avatar>{{cite news |url=http://it.avatar-nusantara.com/2015/04/10/aplikasi-paktor-klaim-miliki-500-ribu-pengguna-di-indonesia |publisher=Avatar Nusantara Technologies |title=Aplikasi Paktor Klaim Miliki 500 Ribu Pengguna di Indonesia}}</ref>\n\nThe app has its own localised slogan in Taiwan, \"\u53cb\u59b3\u9078\u64c7 \u53cb\u4f60\u9078\u64c7\", which means \u2018to choose your friend yourself\u2019.<ref name=Sogi>{{cite news |url=http://www.sogi.com.tw/articles/%E4%BA%9E%E6%B4%B2%E4%BA%A4%E5%8F%8B%E8%BB%9F%E9%AB%94%E9%A0%98%E5%B0%8E%E5%93%81%E7%89%8C_Paktor%E5%85%A8%E6%96%B0%E6%94%B9%E7%89%88_%E4%B8%A6%E9%A6%96%E5%89%B5%E3%80%8C%E5%84%AA%E8%B3%AA%E6%8B%8D%E5%8F%8B%E5%85%AC%E7%B4%84%E3%80%8D/6236821 |publisher=Sogi |title=\u4e9e\u6d32\u4ea4\u53cb\u8edf\u9ad4\u9818\u5c0e\u54c1\u724c Paktor\u5168\u65b0\u6539\u7248 \u4e26\u9996\u5275\u300c\u512a\u8cea\u62cd\u53cb\u516c\u7d04 }}</ref> In January 2015, Paktor created two eye-catching telephone booths near Taipei\u2019s iconic landmark, the Taipei 101, to encourage passers-by to explore the app and provide assurance that the app is a safe and private way to meet new friends across countries<ref name=Damanwoo>{{cite news |url=http://www.damanwoo.com/node/85837 |publisher=Damanwoo |title=\u5728101\u898b\u8b49\u4e0b\u4f86\u5834\u611b\u7684\u9023\u7dda\uff01\u6d6a\u6f2b Paktor \u96fb\u8a71\u4ead\u88dd\u7f6e}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Paktor set a Guinness World record for The World\u2019s Largest Speed Dating Event held in Vietnam.<ref name=PRnews>{{cite news |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/paktor--sagiko-present-a-guinness-world-records-record-attempt---paktor-speed-date-night---the-worlds-largest-speed-dating-event-233023661.html |publisher=PR Newswire |title=Paktor & Sagiko Present A Guinness World Records Record Attempt - Paktor Speed Date Night - The World's Largest Speed Dating Event}}</ref> The event drew 600 participants including local celebrities popular among Vietnamese youth. This record was most recently broken by Calgary Speed Dating Inc. (Canada) at Telus Spark Science Centre in Calgary, Canada, on 14 February 2014<ref name=Guinness>{{cite news |url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/largest-speed-dating-event |publisher=Guinness World Records |title=Largest speed dating event}}</ref>\n\n=== In the media ===\n\nPaktor has received widespread news coverage and been featured on TechCrunch,<ref name=Techcrunch>{{cite news |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/11/17/with-5m-in-funding-tinder-like-paktor-wants-to-get-southeast-asia-using-dating-apps |publisher=TechCrunch |title=With $5M In Funding, Tinder-Like Paktor Wants To Get Southeast Asia Using Dating Apps}}</ref> Bloomberg,<ref name=Bloomberg>{{cite news |url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/money/video/finding-the-perfect-match-on-mobile/vp-AA9UFNl |publisher=Bloomberg |title=Finding the Perfect Match on Mobile}}</ref> CNBC Asia,<ref name=CNBC>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2014/08/29/singapore-entrepreneur-turns-heartache-into-cash.html |publisher=CNBC Asia |title=Singapore entrepreneur turns heartache into cash}}</ref> CNN<ref name=CNN>{{cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/03/22/technology/asia-dating-apps-tinder |publisher=CNN |title=4 ways Asian dating apps are anti-Tinder}}</ref>  and others. The app was positively received in Singapore when it was launched gaining over 25,000 users in the first month.<ref name=Tech3>{{cite news |url=https://www.techinasia.com/paktor |publisher=TechInAsia |title=From heartbreak to Paktor, and how the mobile dating app craze is sweeping across Asia}}</ref> There were also comparisons to established mobile dating apps like Tinder and how it was a similar product and had the same mechanics.\n\nGlobal Dating Insights (GDI) publication regarded Paktor as one of the dating apps to watch. With relatively little competition in Southeast Asia, GDI assesses that the app to have huge potential, crediting the CEO for having \u2018expertly navigated\u2019 the Southeast Asian market with multiple countries each with different cultures, dating habits and languages. \nIn October 2015, Paktor hired two former Meetic senior marketing executives, Jose Ruano and Miguel Mangas, spearheading overseas expansion efforts outside of Asia. The two speak Spanish, which has strategic global importance as 425 million people in the world use Spanish as their first language. Already available in the two most spoken languages, English and Chinese, the hiring acquisitions would allow Paktor to break into European and South American markets.<ref name=GDI>{{cite news |url=http://globaldatinginsights.com/2016/02/12/gdi-dating-industry-power-book-2016-is-now-live/  |publisher=Global Dating Insights |title=Global Dating Insights Power Book 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe conservative nature of Asian cultures has also presented challenges, where regular dating and casual sex is frowned upon.<ref name=Straits>{{cite news |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/no-hanky-panky-dating-apps-woo-investors-with-local-expertise  |publisher=The Straits Times |title=No hanky panky: Dating apps woo investors with local expertise}}</ref>\n\n=== Concerns ===\nIn 2015, a Reddit post highlighted the vulnerability of the GaiGai website due to the lack of security encryptions<ref name=Reddit>{{cite news |url=https://www.reddit.com/r/singapore/comments/32mxlt/psa_do_not_use_gaigai_website_paktors_offline |publisher=Reddit |title=PSA: Do NOT use GaiGai website (Paktor's offline dating service)}}</ref> GaiGai responded that it has since added SSL/TLS encryption. However, some Reddit users commented that more layers of encryption are necessary in order to provide better security for the clientele database. Paktor and GaiGai have since updated their privacy and data protection policy in August 2015<ref name=Paktor>{{cite news |url=http://www.gopaktor.com/#/privacy |publisher=Paktor |title=Privacy Policy)}}</ref><ref name=GaiGai>{{cite news |url=https://letsgaigai.com/#/privacy |publisher=GaiGai |title=Privacy and Data Protection Policy)}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|https://gopaktor.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Mobile social software]]\n[[Category:Geosocial networking]]\n[[Category:Online dating services of Singapore]]\n", "name_user": "Jill NJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected the investor company name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paktor"}
{"title_page": "John Jewkes (MP)", "text_new": "'''John Jewkes'''  (1683\u20131743) was a British lawyer and Whig politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] between 1730 and 1743.\n\nJewkes was baptized on 28 April 1683, the eldest son of Humphrey Jewkes of Petworth and his wife Sarah Whitehead, daughter of John Whitehead of Clandon, Surrey. <ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url =http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/jewkes-john-1683-1743 | title= JEWKES, John (1683-1743), of Petworth, Suss.| publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 2 January 2019 }}</ref > He was educated at [[Eton College]] and was admitted at [[Inner Temple]] on 15 May 1702 and at  [[Peterhouse, Cambridge]] on 25 May1702.<ref name=CU>{{acad|id=  JWKS702J|name=Jewkes, John}}</ref> In 1710, he succeeded to his father's estate. He was admitted at [[Lincolns Inn]] on 21 April 1713. <ref name=LINCS>{{cite book| url = https://archive.org/details/VOL114201799/page/n379 | title = Admissions Register VOL 1 1420-1799 |publisher= The Honourable Society of Lincoln's Inn| date=1896}}</ref>\n\nJewkes, was returned unopposed as a Whig [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bridport (UK Parliament constituency)|Bridport]] at a by-election on 20 February 1730. In Parliament he voted with the Administration in all known divisions. After 1733 he was political agent and intelligence gatherer for the [[Thomas Pelham-Holles, 1st Duke of Newcastle|Duke of Newcastle]]  in the Petworth area. He did not stand at the [[1734 British general election]] but was returned as MP for [[Aldborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldborough]], the Duke's pocket borough, at a by-election on 19 February 1735. He was returned there again unopposed at the [[1741 British general election]].<ref name=HOP/>\n\nJewkes died unmarried on 25 September 1743.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[William Bowles (1686-1748)|William Bowles]]\n | before2 = [[James Pelham]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bridport (UK Parliament constituency)|Bridport]]\n | years =  1730\u2013[[1734 British general election|1734]]\n | with  =  [[William Bowles (1686-1748)|William Bowles]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[William Bowles (1686-1748)|William Bowles]]\n | after2 =  [[Solomon Ashley]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Henry Pelham]]\n | before2 = [[William Jessop (died 1734)|William Jessop]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Aldborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldborough]]\n | years =   1735\u20131743 \n | with  =  [[Andrew Wilkinson (British politician)|Andrew Wilkinson]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Nathaniel Newnham]]\n | after2 = [[Andrew Wilkinson (British politician)|Andrew Wilkinson]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jewkes, John}}\n[[Category:1683 births]]\n[[Category:1743 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Peterhouse, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n [[Category:British MPs 1727\u20131734]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1734\u20131741]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1741\u20131747]]\n", "text_old": "'''John Jewkes'''  (1683\u20131743) was a British lawyer and Whig politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] between 1730 and 1743.\n\nJewkes was baptized on 28 April 1683, the eldest son of Humphrey Jewkes of Petworth and his wife Sarah Whitehead, daughter of John Whitehead of Clandon, Surrey. <ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url =http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/jewkes-john-1683-1743 | title= JEWKES, John (1683-1743), of Petworth, Suss.| publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 2 January 2019 }}</ref > He was educated at [[Eton College]] and was admitted at [[Inner Temple]] on 15 May 1702 and at  [[Peterhouse, Cambridge]] on 25 May1702.<ref name=CU>{{acad|id=  JWKS702J|name=Jewkes, John}}</ref> In 1710, he succeeded to his father\u2019s estate. He was admitted at [[Lincolns Inn]] on 21 April 1713. <ref name=LINCS>{{cite book| url = https://archive.org/details/VOL114201799/page/n379 | title = Admissions Register VOL 1 1420-1799 |publisher= The Honourable Society of Lincoln's Inn| date=1896}}</ref>\n\nJewkes, was returned unopposed as a Whig [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bridport (UK Parliament constituency)|Bridport]] at a by-election on 20 February 1730. In Parliament he voted with the Administration in all known divisions. After 1733 he was political agent and intelligence gatherer for the [[Thomas Pelham-Holles, 1st Duke of Newcastle|Duke of Newcastle]]  in the Petworth area. He did not stand at the [[1734 British general election]] but was returned as MP for [[Aldborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldborough]], the Duke\u2019s pocket borough, at a by-election on 19 February 1735. He was returned there again unopposed at the [[1741 British general election]].<ref name=HOP/>\n\nJewkes died unmarried on 25 September 1743.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[William Bowles (1686-1748)|William Bowles]]\n | before2 = [[James Pelham]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bridport (UK Parliament constituency)|Bridport]]\n | years =  1730\u2013[[1734 British general election|1734]]\n | with  =  [[William Bowles (1686-1748)|William Bowles]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[William Bowles (1686-1748)|William Bowles]]\n | after2 =  [[Solomon Ashley]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Henry Pelham]]\n | before2 = [[William Jessop (died 1734)|William Jessop]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Aldborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldborough]]\n | years =   1735\u20131743 \n | with  =  [[Andrew Wilkinson (British politician)|Andrew Wilkinson]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Nathaniel Newnham]]\n | after2 = [[Andrew Wilkinson (British politician)|Andrew Wilkinson]]\