{"title_page": "Sir Robert Jenkinson, 3rd Baronet", "text_new": "'''Sir Robert Jenkinson, 3rd Baronet''' (1685\u20131717), of Walcot, Charlbury, Oxfordshire and Hawkesbury, Gloucestershire  was a British landowner and Tory politician who sat in the [[House of Commons of Great Britain|House of Commons]] from 1710 to 1717.\n\nJenkinson was the eldest son of  [[Sir Robert Jenkinson, 2nd Baronet]] and his wife Sarah Tomlins, daughter of Thomas Tomlins of Bromley, Middlesex, and was baptised on 23 November 1785.<ref name=Burke>{{cite web| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=seAKAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA94| page=94|title= ''A General and heraldic dictionary of the peerage and baronetage Volume 2'' |author= John Burke}}</ref> He matriculated at [[Trinity College, Oxford]] on 18 February 1703 <ref name=ALUM>{{cite web| url=  https://www.british-history.ac.uk/alumni-oxon/1500-1714/pp793-836| title = 'Jablonski-Juxston', in Alumni Oxonienses 1500-1714, ed. Joseph Foster (Oxford, 1891), pp. 793-836| publisher= British History Online | accessdate= 28 September 2018}}</ref>  In 1705, he was admitted at [[Lincolns Inn]].  He succeeded his  father in the [[Jenkinson baronets|baronetcy]] on 30 January 1710.<ref name=Cokayne3>{{Citation| editor-last=Cokayne| editor-first=George Edward |year=1903 | title= Complete Baronetage volume 3 (1649-1664),  | url=   https://archive.org/details/cu31924092524390/page/n215 |volume=3| location=Exeter | publisher=William Pollard and Co| pages=| accessdate = 9 October 2018}}</ref> He married  by licence dated. 4 February 1712, Henrietta Maria Scarborough, daughter of [[Charles Scarborough]].<ref name=Burke/>\n\nJenkinson succeeded his father as Tory [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Oxfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Oxfordshire]] at a closely contested by-election on 22 February 1710. He voted against the impeachment of [[Henry Sacheverell|Dr Sacheverell]], and on 3 May 1710 presented his county's loyal address to the Queen. He took a leading part in entertaining Sacheverell during his progress through Oxfordshire in July, dining him at Walcot on 19 July. Jenkinson was returned unopposed at the [[1710 British general election]].  He was listed as a \u2018worthy patriot\u2019 who  detected the mismanagements of the previous administration, and as a \u2018Tory patriot\u2019 who opposed  the continuation of the war in 1711. He was a member of the [[October Club]]. He was returned again at the  [[1713 British general election|1713]] but then played little part in Parliament.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url =https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1690-1715/member/jenkinson-sir-robert-1685-1717 | title=JENKINSON, Sir Robert, 3rd Bt. (1685-1717), of Walcot, Charlbury, Oxon. and Hawkesbury, Glos. | publisher= History of Parliament Online (1690-1715)| accessdate = 28 September 2018}}</ref> and  [[1715 British general election|1715]].<ref name = HOP2>{{cite web| url = https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/jenkinson-sir-robert-1685-1717| title= JENKINSON, Sir Robert, 3rd Bt. (1685-1717), of Walcot, Oxon. and Hawkesbury, Glos.| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1715-1754)| accessdate = 28 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nJenkinson died of a fever on 29 October 1717, and was buried at Charlbury. He had no children and was succeeded in the baronetcy by his brother [[Sir Robert Bankes Jenkinson, 4th Baronet|Robert Bankes]]. His widow married [[Charles Eversfield (MP)|Charles Eversfield]] in 1731.<ref name=HOP/> \n  \n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Sir Robert Jenkinson, 2nd Baronet]]\n | before2 = [[Francis Godolphin, 2nd Earl of Godolphin|Viscount Rialton]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Oxfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Oxfordshire]]\n | years =   1717\u2013[[1727 British general election|1727]]\n | with  =  [[Francis Godolphin, 2nd Earl of Godolphin|Viscount Rialton]] 1710\n | with2 =  [[Francis Clerke (MP for Oxfordshire)|Francis Clerke]] 1710-1715\n | with3 = [[James Herbert (died 1721)|James Herbert]] 1715-1717\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Sir Robert Bankes Jenkinson, 4th Baronet|Sir Robert Bankes Jenkinson]] \n | after2 =  [[James Herbert (died 1721)|James Herbert]] \n}}\n{{S-reg|en-bt}}\n{{S-bef| before=[[Sir Robert Jenkinson, 2nd Baronet]]}}\n{{S-ttl| title=[[Jenkinson baronets|Baronet]]<br />'''(of Walcot and Hawkesbury ) | years=1710-1717''' }}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Sir Robert Bankes Jenkinson, 4th Baronet|Sir Robert Bankes Jenkinson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jenkinson, Sir Robert, 3rd Baronet}}\n[[Category:1685 births]]\n[[Category:1717 deaths]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1708\u20131710]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1710\u20131713]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1713\u20131715]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1715\u20131722]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of England]]\n", "text_old": "'''Sir Robert Jenkinson, 3rd Baronet''' (1685\u20131717), of Walcot, Charlbury, Oxfordshire and Hawkesbury, Gloucestershire  was a British landowner and Tory politician who sat in the [[House of Commons of Great Britain|House of Commons]] from 1710 to 1717.\n\nJenkinson was the eldest son of  [[Sir Robert Jenkinson, 2nd Baronet]] and his wife Sarah Tomlins, daughter of Thomas Tomlins of Bromley, Middlesex, and was baptised on 23 November 1785.<ref name=Burke>{{cite web| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=seAKAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA94| page=94|title= ''A General and heraldic dictionary of the peerage and baronetage Volume 2'' |author= John Burke}}</ref> He matriculated at [[Trinity College, Oxford]] on 18 February 1703 <ref name=ALUM>{{cite web| url=  https://www.british-history.ac.uk/alumni-oxon/1500-1714/pp793-836| title = 'Jablonski-Juxston', in Alumni Oxonienses 1500-1714, ed. Joseph Foster (Oxford, 1891), pp. 793-836| publisher= British History Online | accessdate= 28 September 2018}}</ref>  In 1705, he was admitted at [[Lincolns Inn]].  He succeeded his  father in the [[Jenkinson baronets|baronetcy]] on 30 January 1710.<ref name=Cokayne3>{{Citation| editor-last=Cokayne| editor-first=George Edward |year=1903 | title= Complete Baronetage volume 3 (1649-1664),  | url=   https://archive.org/details/cu31924092524390/page/n215 |volume=3| location=Exeter | publisher=William Pollard and Co| pages=| accessdate = 9 October 2018}}</ref> He married  by licence dated. 4 February 1712, Henrietta Maria Scarborough, daughter of [[Charles Scarborough]].<ref name=Burke/>\n\nJenkinson succeeded his father as Tory [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Oxfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Oxfordshire]] at a closely contested by-election on 22 February 1710. He voted against the impeachment of [[Henry Sacheverell|Dr Sacheverell]], and on 3 May 1710 presented his county\u2019s loyal address to the Queen. He took a leading part in entertaining Sacheverell during his progress through Oxfordshire in July, dining him at Walcot on 19 July. Jenkinson was returned unopposed at the [[1710 British general election]].  He was listed as a \u2018worthy patriot\u2019 who  detected the mismanagements of the previous administration, and as a \u2018Tory patriot\u2019 who opposed  the continuation of the war in 1711. He was a member of the [[October Club]]. He was returned again at the  [[1713 British general election|1713]] but then played little part in Parliament.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url =https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1690-1715/member/jenkinson-sir-robert-1685-1717 | title=JENKINSON, Sir Robert, 3rd Bt. (1685-1717), of Walcot, Charlbury, Oxon. and Hawkesbury, Glos. | publisher= History of Parliament Online (1690-1715)| accessdate = 28 September 2018}}</ref> and  [[1715 British general election|1715]].<ref name = HOP2>{{cite web| url = https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/jenkinson-sir-robert-1685-1717| title= JENKINSON, Sir Robert, 3rd Bt. (1685-1717), of Walcot, Oxon. and Hawkesbury, Glos.| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1715-1754)| accessdate = 28 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nJenkinson died of a fever on 29 October 1717, and was buried at Charlbury. He had no children and was succeeded in the baronetcy by his brother [[Sir Robert Bankes Jenkinson, 4th Baronet|Robert Bankes]]. His widow married [[Charles Eversfield (MP)|Charles Eversfield]] in 1731.<ref name=HOP/> \n  \n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Sir Robert Jenkinson, 2nd Baronet]]\n | before2 = [[Francis Godolphin, 2nd Earl of Godolphin|Viscount Rialton]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Oxfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Oxfordshire]]\n | years =   1717\u2013[[1727 British general election|1727]]\n | with  =  [[Francis Godolphin, 2nd Earl of Godolphin|Viscount Rialton]] 1710\n | with2 =  [[Francis Clerke (MP for Oxfordshire)|Francis Clerke]] 1710-1715\n | with3 = [[James Herbert (died 1721)|James Herbert]] 1715-1717\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Sir Robert Bankes Jenkinson, 4th Baronet|Sir Robert Bankes Jenkinson]] \n | after2 =  [[James Herbert (died 1721)|James Herbert]] \n}}\n{{S-reg|en-bt}}\n{{S-bef| before=[[Sir Robert Jenkinson, 2nd Baronet]]}}\n{{S-ttl| title=[[Jenkinson baronets|Baronet]]<br />'''(of Walcot and Hawkesbury ) | years=1710-1717''' }}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Sir Robert Bankes Jenkinson, 4th Baronet|Sir Robert Bankes Jenkinson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jenkinson, Sir Robert, 3rd Baronet}}\n[[Category:1685 births]]\n[[Category:1717 deaths]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1708\u20131710]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1710\u20131713]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1713\u20131715]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1715\u20131722]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of England]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's",